05029nam a22007335i 9780887558764DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2020446454  a97808875587647 a10.1515/97808875587642doi  a(DE-B1597)664627  a(OCoLC)1150906273  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA00aE99.C6bL75 2020 4aE99.C6bL83 2020 7aHIS0280002bisacsh04a305.897/3330713112231 aLuby, Brittany, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDammed :bThe Politics of Loss and Survival in Anishinaabe Territory /cBrittany Luby. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Studies in Native History ;v2100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tA Message from Chief Lorraine Cobiness -- tLooking Out from Anishinaabe Territory -- tBy Water we Inhabit this Place -- tRising River, Receding Access -- tPower Lost and Power Gained -- tLabouring to Keep the Reserve Alive -- tWaste Accumulation in a Changed River -- tMother Work and Managing Environmental Change -- tSo that Our Next Generation Will Know -- tAcknowledgements -- tA Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDammed explores Canada’s hydroelectric boom in the Lake of the Woods area. It complicates narratives of increasing affluence in postwar Canada, revealing that the inverse was true for Indigenous communities along the Winnipeg River. Dammed makes clear that hydroelectric generating stations were designed to serve settler populations. Governments and developers excluded the Anishinabeg from planning and operations and failed to consider how power production might influence the health and economy of their communities. By so doing, Canada and Ontario thwarted a future that aligned with the terms of treaty, a future in which both settlers and the Anishinabeg might thrive in shared territories. The same hydroelectric development that powered settler communities flooded manomin fields, washed away roads, and compromised fish populations. Anishinaabe families responded creatively to manage the government-sanctioned environmental change and survive the resulting economic loss. Luby reveals these responses to dam development, inviting readers to consider how resistance might be expressed by individuals and families, and across gendered and generational lines. Luby weaves text, testimony, and experience together, grounding this historical work in the territory of her paternal ancestors, lands she calls home. With evidence drawn from archival material, oral history, and environmental observation, Dammed invites readers to confront Canadian colonialism in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHydroelectric power plantsxEconomic aspectszLake of the Woods. 0aHydroelectric power plantsxEnvironmental aspectszLake of the Woods. 0aIndigenous peopleszLake of the WoodsxEconomic conditions. 0aIndigenous peopleszLake of the WoodsxSocial conditions. 0aWater resources developmentxEconomic aspectszLake of the Woods. 0aWater resources developmentxEnvironmental aspectszLake of the Woods. 0aWater securityzLake of the Woods. 0aWater-supplyzLake of the Woods. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  abooks about hydro dams in CA.  achange.  adestruction.  aenvironmental racism.  ainfrastructure.  arivers.  ascholarly research.  awater.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473740uh